# Handy Calculation
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/pianoguy/image_1579076714.png)

Thank [SNaveenMathew](https://leetcode.com/SNaveenMathew) for the [explanation](https://leetcode.com/problems/sqrtx/discuss/480993/A-Chinese-Traditional-Solution:-Yanghui-Suancao-()/1077352) below:
> Here's a mathematical explanation for a 4 digit number abcd
The result starts with y = floor(sqrt(ab)). Therefore, the result is of the form 10*y + z, where z is a number in range [0, 9]
(10y+z)^2 = 100*y^2 + 2*10*yz + z^2
We already identified y, so subtract 100*y^2 from abcd to obtain remainder (say, rem). Now 2*10*yz + z^2 can be written as (2*10y + z) * z. Iterate from z = 0 to 9 (inclusive) to find the value z such that the resulting product is less than or equal to rem. There's our answer! This approach can be extended to any number of digits (odd or even).

# Coding (C#)

```csharp
public class Solution
{
    public int MySqrt(int x)
    {
        var result = 0;
        var (shang, yu, lian, fa) = (0, 0, 0, 1);
        while (x / fa >= 100)
        {
            fa *= 100;
        }
        while (fa > 0)
        {
            result *= 10;
            lian += shang;
            lian *= 10;
            yu = x % fa;
            x /= fa;
            shang = GuessShang(x, lian);
            lian += shang;
            result += shang;
            x = (x - shang * lian) * fa + yu;
            fa /= 100;
        }
        return result;
    }

    private static int GuessShang(int x, int lian)
    {
        var shang = 0;
        while ((lian + shang) * shang < x)
        {
            shang++;
        }
        if ((lian + shang) * shang > x)
        {
            shang--;
        }
        return shang;
    }
}
```

