Carmack's method is a fast way to find the inverse square root of a float number:

[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_inverse_square_root][1]

Carmack's method is fast because:

 1. The initial guess is super accurate.
 2. Does not use division.
 3. Does not use loops.

Note that Carmack's method is no longer useful nowadays and this is just for fun.


    class Solution {
        public:
        int mySqrt(int x) {
            uint64_t i;
            double x2, y;
            x2 = x * 0.5;
            y = x;
            i = *(uint64_t *) &y;
            i = 0x5fe6eb50c7b537a9 - (i >> 1); // This magic number is taken from wikipedia.
            y = *(double *) &i; // initial guess of the inverse square root
            y = y * (1.5 - (x2 * y * y)); // Newton for inverse square root.
            y = y * (1.5 - (x2 * y * y));
            y = y * (1.5 - (x2 * y * y));
            y = y * (1.5 - (x2 * y * y)); // repeate 4 times to get enough precision.
            return x * y;
        }
    };


  [1]: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_inverse_square_root

