1. First we solve this problem using linear search, we have to find the sqrt(x)
	here y^2 = x, so we need to find the value y i.e (y*y <= x)
 ```
 class Solution {
    public int mySqrt(int x) {
        long y=0;
        while(y*y<=x)
            y++;
        return (int)y-1;
    }
}
```
Time Complexity in case of linear search will be O(x).

2. Using Binary Search
	* we search sqrt(x) in range 1 to x/2, so low=1;
	* Value of sqrt(x) will never be grater than x/2, so we will take high=x/2;
```
class Solution {
    public int mySqrt(int x) {
        if(x==0)
            return 0;
        long l=1, h=x/2;
        int output=1;
        while(l<=h){
            long mid = l+(h-l)/2;
            long sqrt = mid*mid;
            if(sqrt == x)
                return (int)mid;
            else if(sqrt<x){
                output=(int)mid;
                l=mid+1;
            }
            else
                h=mid-1;
        } 
        return output;
    }
}
```

Time Complexity using binary search would be log(x).
